    id: 'new-8',
    slug: 'compound-interest',
    name: 'Compound Interest',
    category: 'Finance',
    subcategory: 'Investing Basics',
    definition: 'Compound interest is the interest calculated on the initial principal and also on the accumulated interest of previous periods. It is often called interest on interest and is the most powerful force in finance. Unlike simple interest which is calculated only on the principal amount, compound interest grows exponentially because each period interest is earned on a larger base. The frequency of compounding quarterly, monthly, daily dramatically affects total returns over long periods. Compound interest applies to both investments where you earn interest on your earnings and debts where unpaid interest capitalizes, increasing what you owe.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Compound interest is like a snowball rolling downhill. It starts small but as it rolls, it picks up more snow, gets bigger, and picks up snow even faster. Your money grows not just on what you put in but on all the growth that came before.',
    example: 'If you invest $10,000 at age 25 earning 8% annually compounded, by age 65 it grows to $217,245. If you wait until age 35 to start the same $10,000 only grows to $100,626. The 10-year delay costs you over $116,000 because you miss a decade of compounding on your earnings.',
    whyItMatters: 'Albert Einstein reportedly called compound interest the eighth wonder of the world. It is the single most important concept for building long-term wealth. Understanding compound interest drives critical financial behaviors: starting to save early, being consistent with investments, letting investments grow without interruption, and avoiding high-interest debt like credit cards where compounding works against you.',
    formula: 'A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)',
    formulaDescription: 'A = final amount, P = principal (initial investment), r = annual interest rate (decimal), n = number of times compounded per year, t = number of years. For example, $1,000 invested at 8% compounded monthly for 30 years: $1,000(1 + 0.08/12)^(12*30) = $11,076.',
    relatedTerms: ['time-value-of-money', 'simple-interest', 'rule-of-72', 'discounted-cash-flow', 'present-value', 'roi'],
    interviewQuestions: ['How does compounding frequency affect total returns?', 'Explain the Rule of 72 and how it relates to compound interest.', 'How does compound interest work against you with credit card debt?', 'What is the impact of taxes on compound interest in investment accounts?', 'How would you explain compound interest to someone who has never invested?'],
    commonMistakes: ['Underestimating the effect of fees on compounding a 1% fee can reduce final portfolio value by 25-30% over 30 years.', 'Starting too late the difference between starting at 25 vs 35 is often hundreds of thousands of dollars.', 'Interrupting compounding through early withdrawals or market timing during downturns.', 'Confusing simple interest with compound interest simple interest dramatically underperforms long-term.'],
    sharkTankExample: 'When Mark Cuban invested in BeatBox Beverages, he structured it as a convertible note with compound interest. The founders understood that if they did not hit milestones, the compounding interest would significantly dilute their equity, motivating them to execute.',
    realCompanyExample: 'Warren Buffett built his $100B+ fortune through compound interest. He started investing at age 11, consistently compounded returns of ~20% annually for 70+ years. He famously said that his wealth came from living in the US, good genes, and compound interest.',
    visualDiagram: 'Year 1: $1,000 principal -> $80 interest -> Total $1,080 || Year 2: $1,080 -> $86.40 interest -> Total $1,166.40 || Year 3: $1,166.40 -> $93.31 interest -> Total $1,259.71 || Year 10: ~$2,159 || Year 20: ~$4,661 || Year 30: ~$10,063',
    quickSummary: 'Compound interest earns interest on previous interest, creating exponential growth over time. Starting early, being consistent, and avoiding interruptions maximize the compounding effect, making it the most powerful wealth-building force in finance.',
    faqs: [
      { question: 'What is the Rule of 72?', answer: 'The Rule of 72 estimates how long it takes to double your money. Divide 72 by the annual interest rate. At 8%, it takes ~9 years 72/8 = 9 to double. At 12%, it takes ~6 years.' },
      { question: 'How does inflation affect compound interest?', answer: 'Real return = nominal return minus inflation. If you earn 7% but inflation is 3%, your real compounding rate is 4%. This is why investing in assets that outpace inflation is crucial.' },
      { question: 'What is the best compounding frequency?', answer: 'More frequent compounding yields slightly higher returns. Daily compounding is best, but the difference is small. Continuous compounding using e provides the theoretical maximum.' },
    ],
