    id: 'new-9',
    slug: 'api-architecture',
    name: 'API Architecture (REST vs GraphQL vs gRPC)',
    category: 'Tech Explained',
    subcategory: 'Software Architecture',
    definition: 'API architecture defines how software applications communicate with each other. The three dominant modern API architectures are REST, GraphQL, and gRPC. REST Representational State Transfer uses HTTP methods GET, POST, PUT, DELETE to manipulate resources identified by URLs. It is stateless and cacheable but can require multiple round-trips. GraphQL, developed by Meta, allows clients to request exactly the data they need in a single query, reducing over-fetching and under-fetching. gRPC, developed by Google, uses Protocol Buffers for efficient binary serialization and HTTP/2 for streaming, making it ideal for high-performance microservices communication.',
    simpleExplanation: 'APIs are like restaurant waiters. REST is ordering from a fixed menu you get what they serve. GraphQL is a custom chef you say what ingredients you want and they make exactly that dish. gRPC is a conveyor belt with pre-packed meals optimized for speed and efficiency in the kitchen.',
    example: 'A mobile app needs user profile and their recent orders. REST requires two requests: GET /users/123 and GET /users/123/orders. GraphQL needs one query: user(id:123){name,email,orders{date,total}}. gRPC sends a compact binary message like getUserWithOrders{userId:123} and gets back structured data in milliseconds.',
    whyItMatters: 'Choosing the right API architecture affects development speed, application performance, bandwidth usage, and user experience. REST is the most widely adopted and understood. GraphQL excels for complex data requirements, especially in mobile apps where bandwidth matters. gRPC is optimal for internal microservices where performance and type safety are critical.',
    relatedTerms: ['microservices', 'restful-api', 'graphql', 'grpc', 'http', 'protocol-buffers', 'api-design'],
    interviewQuestions: ['When would you choose GraphQL over REST?', 'What are the performance advantages of gRPC over REST?', 'How does GraphQL handle N+1 query problems?', 'What are the security implications of GraphQL compared to REST?', 'How do you version APIs in REST vs GraphQL?'],
    commonMistakes: ['Using GraphQL when REST would suffice GraphQL adds complexity that may not be needed for simple CRUD apps.', 'Ignoring caching REST leverages HTTP caching naturally; GraphQL requires custom caching solutions.', 'Using gRPC for external/browser clients gRPC requires HTTP/2 and is primarily designed for server-to-server communication.'],
    sharkTankExample: 'A startup pitches an API integration platform that auto-generates REST, GraphQL, and gRPC interfaces from a single schema definition. The sharks are impressed by the time savings for enterprise integration teams.',
    realCompanyExample: 'GitHub API v4 moved from REST to GraphQL. This reduced the number of API calls needed for common workflows from 5-10 to 1-2. GitHub mobile app saw dramatic improvements in load times due to precise data fetching.',
    visualDiagram: 'Client Application -> REST: Multiple HTTP endpoints, over-fetching possible, versioned URLs -> API Gateway -> Server || Client -> GraphQL: Single /graphql endpoint, client-specified fields, no over-fetching -> Resolver Functions -> Server || Client -> gRPC: Single connection, binary Protocol Buffers, bidirectional streaming -> Service Methods -> Server',
    quickSummary: 'REST, GraphQL, and gRPC are the three dominant API architectures. REST uses HTTP verbs for resource manipulation, GraphQL enables precise client-driven queries, and gRPC provides high-performance binary communication ideal for microservices.',
    faqs: [
      { question: 'Which API architecture is most popular?', answer: 'REST is the most widely adopted due to its simplicity and maturity. GraphQL is rapidly growing, especially for complex frontend applications. gRPC is dominant in microservices ecosystems.' },
      { question: 'Can you use multiple API architectures together?', answer: 'Yes. Many companies expose public REST APIs for general use, offer GraphQL for complex queries, and use gRPC for internal service-to-service communication.' },
      { question: 'Which is fastest?', answer: 'gRPC is fastest due to binary serialization and HTTP/2 multiplexing. GraphQL is typically slower than REST for simple queries but faster for complex nested data requirements.' },
    ],
    references: ['Fielding, R. (2000). Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures.', 'Meta. (2015). GraphQL Specification.', 'Google. (2015). gRPC: A High Performance, Open Source Universal RPC Framework.'],
    tags: ['API', 'REST', 'GraphQL', 'gRPC', 'microservices', 'backend', 'protocol'],
